Here's a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:
```c
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    int wordCount = 0;
    string wordToCount;

    // Open the text file for reading
    ifstream file("example.txt");

    // Read the first line of the file to get the word to count
    string line;
    while (getline(file, line)) {
        istringstream iss(line);
        while (iss >> wordToCount >> wordCount) {
            cout << "Word: " << wordToCount << " Occurrences: " << wordCount << endl;
            wordCount = 0;
        }
    }

    // Close the file
    file.close();

    return 0;
}
```
In this example, the program reads the text file "example.txt" line by line. The first line of the file is read and the word to count is extracted from the line using an istringstream. The program then counts the number of occurrences of the word in the rest of the file by reading each line and using the istringstream to extract the word and increment the count. The program then outputs the word and the number of occurrences. The program repeats this process until the end of the file is reached.

